      <span class="topic-index">01</span>
      <div>
        <div class="talk-card-meta">
          <span class="talk-status">Presented</span>
          <span>Advanced · Multi-agent systems</span>
        </div>
        <h2>Orchestrating a Game Dev Team Using Microsoft Agent Framework</h2>
        <p>What happens when I want to build a game but do not have a studio? I build the studio from AI agents. This practical case follows specialised Game Designer, Developer, QA, Producer, and Reviewer agents working on one product.</p>
        <p class="topic-outcome">Takeaway: design clear roles, shared artifacts, review gates, and stop criteria so multi-agent speed does not become multi-agent chaos, and understand where the human engineer remains indispensable.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
    <article class="topic-card">
      <span class="topic-index">02</span>
      <div>
        <div class="talk-card-meta">
          <span class="talk-status">Presented</span>
          <span>Beginner · Mindfulness for developers</span>
        </div>
        <h2>Working Like a Buddha: Less Stress, More Joy</h2>
        <p>Software developers move constantly between code, chat, meetings, reviews, incidents, and production. This down-to-earth session translates Buddhist principles such as attention, simplicity, and presence into ordinary engineering work, without incense or vague promises.</p>
        <p class="topic-outcome">Takeaway: recognise the cost of context switching and use small, practical habits to bring more focus, calm, and enjoyment to coding, reviews, meetings, and incidents.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

